<div id="review_1507675479" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1507675479" />
    <a title="Douglas Cosby" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11200007-douglas-cosby"><img alt="Douglas Cosby" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1457467008p2/11200007.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1507675479?book_show_action=true">Jan 12, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Douglas Cosby" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Douglas Cosby" href="/user/show/11200007-douglas-cosby">Douglas Cosby</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1507675479" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9527610888378044231">I first read this book back in 2015. I decided to re-read it because I was enjoying the quaintness of Bertrand Russell&apos;s &quot;The Conquest of Happiness.&quot; Russell&apos;s book is a precursor to all the self help books that come in the late 20th century, and it was interesting and refreshing to see someone as intellectual as Russell to think seriously and philisophically about personal happiness. It reminded me how I felt when I first read this short memoir on Styron&apos;s near-suicidal plunge into depression, </span>
  <span id="freeText9527610888378044231" style="display:none">I first read this book back in 2015. I decided to re-read it because I was enjoying the quaintness of Bertrand Russell's "The Conquest of Happiness." Russell's book is a precursor to all the self help books that come in the late 20th century, and it was interesting and refreshing to see someone as intellectual as Russell to think seriously and philisophically about personal happiness. It reminded me how I felt when I first read this short memoir on Styron's near-suicidal plunge into depression, so I decided to read it again. It was just as good the second time. Styron spends most of the book explaining the feelings and real-ness of depression in innocent, yet literary, language. Our collective knowledge about depression was still in its early days in the late 80's when Styron wrote this, similar to the societal state of self-help when Russell wrote his book. Styron's objectivity and naivete are wonderful, and I always love to read smart people discussing complicated topics before society creates the politcally-correct party line. A very cool window into time and into Styron's private life.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9527610888378044231" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


