    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2808305629" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2808305629" />
    <a title="Col" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/56337647-col"><img alt="Col" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1542825678p2/56337647.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2808305629?book_show_action=true">May 18, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Col" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Col" href="/user/show/56337647-col">Col</a>
      </span>

          added it


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780374135027" href="/book/show/3025281-darkness-visible">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/56337647-col?shelf=fantastical-fiction">fantastical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/56337647-col?shelf=other-fiction">other-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2808305629" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11722625997136816350">Spoiler review:<br/><br/>I&apos;m at a loss what to write. This has been by far the most baffling of Golding&apos;s books to me, taking the opaque parts of Free Fall and turning them up even higher. The common thread is people convinced their lives are predetermined, but through radically different lenses. Matty believes he is chosen by God for some purpose obscure to him, Sophy has a nihilistic-materialist view and only feels real joy when she feels her violent impulses are in accordance with the structure of the </span>
  <span id="freeText11722625997136816350" style="display:none">Spoiler review:<br /><br />I'm at a loss what to write. This has been by far the most baffling of Golding's books to me, taking the opaque parts of Free Fall and turning them up even higher. The common thread is people convinced their lives are predetermined, but through radically different lenses. Matty believes he is chosen by God for some purpose obscure to him, Sophy has a nihilistic-materialist view and only feels real joy when she feels her violent impulses are in accordance with the structure of the universe, finally Pedigree is tormented a pedophilia he alternately believes is a horrific biological impulse and an artistic appreciation of true beauty. But what is it all building toward? Matty's death seems to confirm all his beliefs/delusions of being chosen, and is even further confirmed by Pedigree's deathbed vision of Matty's healing fire consuming him. Sophy's thwarted scheme of kidnapping/child murder ends up being just as instrumental to Matty's salvation as Matty's own strange actions. There is clearly some kind of structural thing going on with Matty emerging as the sole survivor of a fire at the beginning of his life and dying in fire while saving another, and the possible murder of a child by Matty in school and Sophy's imaginary murder of a child right before Matty's death, but what of it? There are so many other elements I find equally baffling. Toni is obviously one of the things that makes Sophy even more opposite of Matty (two separate beings with an inseparable connection) vs the isolated man with two differing faces, but she has no perspective within the story and appears only very briefly at the beginning and end of Sophy's section. What is the point of Pedigree? Matty sees his "betrayal" as one of his stigmata, and he witnesses Matty's transfiguration, but he plays no obvious role in Matty's salvation. Maybe he's there as a counterpoint to Sophy, to show that he remains salvable in comparison to Sophy's descent into evil? But how does that connect to the overall thread of predestination? And what of the nurse in Matty's childhood who thinks (paraphrasing) "Matty thinks I'm two different people". Why did Matty discard his first bible for the one with wooden covers?<br /><br />The Matty segment was at least enjoyable, if confusing. That at least mirrored his warped view of things, and lots of segments in it were wonderful, like the initial blaze, the miniature world of the ironworks, the journey across Australia. The journal part meandered between ridiculously hokey and sincerely spooky. The Sophy segment, by contrast, was a trial. It started off fine, but once they returned from their grandmother's house, it just got more and more predictable and trying. It was just a smooth downfall into depravity as we see every way in which Sophy is Matty's exact opposite. It felt padded, which was something I never thought I'd say about a Golding novel. It at least had an interesting ending with the conversation between her and her father, in which I could feel at least a little bit of disgusted pity for her, like one feels for a struggling de-limbed insect. The last bit was an improvement, with more Matty and Pedigree, and Sim was an alright perspective, being a sort of redux of the torn quality of Free Fall to round things out.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11722625997136816350" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


