        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4317684976" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2906118769545595084">Darkness Visible (the title a quote from Paradise Lost) was Golding’s comeback novel (1979) after a gap of twelve years. <br/><br/>It’s a book in three sections. The middle section, charting the growth of twins from childhood to adulthood, is scintillating; but the other two parts suffer from what seems like intentional obscurity. Part one meanders seemingly at random; and part three is almost impossibly convoluted. <br/><br/>Golding weaves a complicated story and tells it in far from the most coherent way. It’s ha</span>
  <span id="freeText2906118769545595084" style="display:none">Darkness Visible (the title a quote from Paradise Lost) was Golding’s comeback novel (1979) after a gap of twelve years. <br /><br />It’s a book in three sections. The middle section, charting the growth of twins from childhood to adulthood, is scintillating; but the other two parts suffer from what seems like intentional obscurity. Part one meanders seemingly at random; and part three is almost impossibly convoluted. <br /><br />Golding weaves a complicated story and tells it in far from the most coherent way. It’s hard to determine where and how the narratives in parts one and two intersect (though intersect they do, and crucially to the plot), and we are left with a number of mysteries, puzzles and conundrums.<br /><br />Darkness Visible, though yielding many great moments, is a far cry from the lucid, sunlit clarity of The Lord of the Flies (1954).</span>
  <a data-text-id="2906118769545595084" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


