<span id="freeTextContainer14023825938018830318">I came to this after seeing Lars Iyer describe it as one of a handful of &apos;half-mad&apos; modern English novels. Well, he&apos;s not wrong - though I&apos;d question his use of &apos;half&apos;. It&apos;s a damaged book, full of intensities, characterised by a kind of warped, flailing, questing - a search for answers, answers to questions that are, at best, incoherent, at worst, non-existent. <br/><br/>&quot;We’re all mad, the whole damned race. We’re wrapped in illusions, delusions, confusions about the penetrability of partitions, we’re a</span>
  <span id="freeText14023825938018830318" style="display:none">I came to this after seeing Lars Iyer describe it as one of a handful of 'half-mad' modern English novels. Well, he's not wrong - though I'd question his use of 'half'. It's a damaged book, full of intensities, characterised by a kind of warped, flailing, questing - a search for answers, answers to questions that are, at best, incoherent, at worst, non-existent. <br /><br />"We’re all mad, the whole damned race. We’re wrapped in illusions, delusions, confusions about the penetrability of partitions, we’re all mad and in solitary confinement.” “We think we know.” “Know? That’s worse than an atom bomb, and always was."</span>
  <a data-text-id="14023825938018830318" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

