  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1739253923?book_show_action=true">Aug 25, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Neale" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Neale" href="/user/show/5236138-neale">Neale</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780571114542" href="/book/show/144702.Darkness_Visible">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5236138-neale?shelf=literary-fiction">literary-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1739253923" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14518621597722068372">This book came out after a longish period of creative block for Golding, and it feels like burst of rather fetid water from a clogged pipe.<br/><br/>It is a very strange and dark book, and sometimes a heavy-handed one, written in an intense, knotty, poetic, visceral language. It is always compelling, even when it is being oddly unpleasant – one feels that there are issues squirming just under the surface that Golding doesn’t want to address directly, but is glad to get out of the way. <br/><br/>The Australian secti</span>
  <span id="freeText14518621597722068372" style="display:none">This book came out after a longish period of creative block for Golding, and it feels like burst of rather fetid water from a clogged pipe.<br /><br />It is a very strange and dark book, and sometimes a heavy-handed one, written in an intense, knotty, poetic, visceral language. It is always compelling, even when it is being oddly unpleasant – one feels that there are issues squirming just under the surface that Golding doesn’t want to address directly, but is glad to get out of the way. <br /><br />The Australian section reads like a weird parody of Patrick White's 'Riders in the Chariot'. Golding denied any influence, but it's pretty hard to miss.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14518621597722068372" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
