              <span id="reviewTextContainer2768711752" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2141168946340299471">Like its protagonists, this is a book of two halves: the first half being a staggeringly poignant and poetic Bildungsroman loaded with striking imagery, thrilling set-pieces and gorgeous, funny, original characters you just want to live with forever. And then it stops, and the second half is a kind of grotty domestic terrorist narrative with occasional flashes of brilliance. <br/><br/>The preoccupation with sex will be surprising to anyone, like myself, who is coming to this cold other than school age dal</span>
  <span id="freeText2141168946340299471" style="display:none">Like its protagonists, this is a book of two halves: the first half being a staggeringly poignant and poetic Bildungsroman loaded with striking imagery, thrilling set-pieces and gorgeous, funny, original characters you just want to live with forever. And then it stops, and the second half is a kind of grotty domestic terrorist narrative with occasional flashes of brilliance. <br /><br />The preoccupation with sex will be surprising to anyone, like myself, who is coming to this cold other than school age dalliances with Lord of the Flies. Less surprising is the continuing theme of children’s corruption by the adult world. In Lord of the Flies, Golding suggested that humans were in fact animals - amoral and always teetering on the verge of chaos. But in the twenty years between that book and this, he seems to have given us a little more credit: we don’t just slip into the darkness. We seek it out; we invite it in.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2141168946340299471" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


